    title: "Pressure Injury Prevention and Management in LTC",
    cellular: { title: "Pressure Injury Staging and Prevention", content: "Pressure injuries (formerly pressure ulcers or decubitus ulcers) are localized damage to the skin and/or underlying tissue, usually over a bony prominence, resulting from sustained pressure or pressure combined with shear and friction. The National Pressure Injury Advisory Panel (NPIAP) staging system includes: Stage 1 (non-blanchable erythema of intact skin), Stage 2 (partial-thickness skin loss with exposed dermis - appears as shallow open ulcer or blister), Stage 3 (full-thickness skin loss - subcutaneous fat visible, no exposed bone/tendon/muscle), Stage 4 (full-thickness tissue loss with exposed bone, tendon, or muscle), Unstageable (full-thickness loss obscured by slough or eschar - cannot determine depth until debrided), and Deep Tissue Pressure Injury (DTPI - intact or non-intact skin with persistent deep red/maroon/purple discoloration or blood-filled blister from damage to underlying tissue). Pressure injuries in LTC are considered a quality indicator and may be classified as a never event. Prevention focuses on the Braden Scale assessment (scores ≤18 indicate risk, ≤12 high risk), regular repositioning, pressure redistribution surfaces, nutritional optimization, moisture management, and skin inspection. Key nursing interventions include repositioning every 2 hours (or per individualized schedule), keeping skin clean and dry, elevating heels off the bed, and ensuring adequate nutrition (protein 1.25-1.5 g/kg/day for prevention)." },
